sols_latex:
Following the definition of a cdf (see the hint), we compute

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $\lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} F(x) = a$ so $a = 0$
\end{itemize}

and

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} F(x) = b$ so $b=1$.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  To impose continuity at $x=1$, we need
  $\lim_{x \rightarrow 1} F(x) = F(1) = b = 1$. Obviously
  $\lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+} F(x) = 1$. So looking at the left limit will
  give us \emph{k}:
\end{itemize}

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \rightarrow 1^-} F(x) = \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^-} k \arctan x = k \arctan 1
\end{align*}
Therefore \emph{k} = 1/(arctan 1)'', or simply $k = \frac4{\pi}$.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  Since arctan is non-decreasing, so is \emph{F}.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Hence our final answer is}

$a=0,\quad b=1,\quad k = \frac{4}{\pi}.$

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH105/April_2012/CDF.png}
\end{description}

\emph{As a remark, it is important to know the exact trig values for
special angles. Here\begin{align*}
\tan \frac{\pi}{4} = 1
\end{align*} so
$\arctan 1 = \frac{\pi}{4}$.}

statement_latex:
Consider the function

\begin{align*}
F(x) = \begin{cases}
a & \text{if } x < 0, \\
k \arctan x & \text{if } 0 \leq x \leq 1, \\
b & \text{if } x \geq 1.
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\textbf{(a)} Find the values of \emph{a}, \emph{k} and \emph{b} for
which \emph{F} is a valid cummulative distribution function of a
continuous random variable. Then sketch the graph of \emph{F}.
